parsedWorkout.title: Classic Bodybuilding: Chest + Triceps (60 min)
parsedWorkout.description: Hypertrophy-focused session prioritizing heavy presses for chest thickness, then isolation for full pec contraction and triceps volume.

exercises.notes: Use a controlled 2–3 sec lower, brief pause near the chest, then press hard. Keep shoulder blades squeezed back and down.
Set the bench to a moderate incline (~20–35°). Lower dumbbells to upper-chest line; avoid flaring elbows excessively.
Slight bend in elbows, big chest stretch at the bottom, then bring arms together without clanking dumbbells. Keep tension on pecs.
Set cables slightly below shoulder height. Cross hands slightly at the finish for peak contraction; avoid shrugging.
Hands just inside shoulder width. Tuck elbows 30–45° from torso; think 'push the bar back' to emphasize triceps.
Lock elbows to your sides and fully extend at the bottom without letting shoulders roll forward. Control the return.

tips: Work 0–2 reps from failure on most sets; keep 1–2 reps in reserve on the first heavy compound to maintain performance across sets.
Progression: when you hit the top of the rep range for all sets with clean form, add 2.5–5% load next session.
Use classic bodybuilding tempo: controlled eccentrics (2–3 seconds) and strong, deliberate contractions—especially on flyes and crossovers.
Keep total rest longer on heavy presses (90–120s) and shorter on isolation (60–75s) to balance strength output and hypertrophy stimulus.

parsedWorkout.title: Classic Bodybuilding: Back + Biceps (60 min)
parsedWorkout.description: Hypertrophy-focused back and biceps session using classic bodybuilding rep ranges, controlled eccentrics, and moderate rest to build and maintain size and strength.

exercises.notes: Barbell bent over row: hinge to a stable torso angle, brace hard, pull elbows toward hips; 2–3 sec controlled lower.
Lat pulldown: slight lean back, drive elbows down and in; pause 1 sec at the bottom without shrugging.
Seated cable row: keep chest tall, initiate by pulling shoulder blades back, then finish with elbows; don’t rock the torso.
Cable face pull: pull toward upper face/forehead, elbows high; focus on rear delts/upper back and smooth reps.
Machine row: keep shoulders down/back, full stretch at the front, hard squeeze at peak contraction for 1 sec.
Barbell curl: keep elbows slightly in front of ribs, avoid swinging; stop 1–2 reps shy of form breakdown.
Incline dumbbell curl: let arms hang back for a full stretch; supinate hard and control the eccentric.

tips: Use a controlled tempo (about 2–3 seconds down) on most sets to match classic bodybuilding tension and reduce momentum.
Keep 1–2 reps in reserve on early sets; push closer to technical failure only on the last set of an exercise.
Prioritize scapular control (down/back) on rows and pulldowns to keep tension on lats/upper back instead of biceps and traps.
Progression: add 1 rep per set until you hit the top of the rep range, then increase load slightly next session.

parsedWorkout.title: Classic Bodybuilding Delts (45 min)
parsedWorkout.description: Shoulder-focused hypertrophy session emphasizing a heavy overhead press followed by high-quality volume for all three delt heads using dumbbells, barbell, cables, and leverage machine.

exercises.notes: Brace glutes and core; keep forearms vertical; stop 1 rep shy of grinding (RIR 1–2).
Use a controlled 2–3 sec lower; avoid locking out hard to keep tension on delts.
Rotate smoothly; keep elbows slightly in front of torso; don’t over-arch low back.
Lead with elbows; slight lean forward; stop around shoulder height; control the lowering phase.
Set cable slightly behind you; raise in the scapular plane; keep traps relaxed and down.
Hinge to near-parallel torso; keep a soft elbow bend; squeeze rear delts at the top without shrugging.

tips: Use classic bodybuilding effort: compounds at ~RIR 1–2, isolations at ~RIR 0–1 with clean form.
Prioritize range of motion and controlled eccentrics (2–3 seconds down) on raises and flies for better delt stimulus.
Progress weekly by adding 1 rep per set until you hit the top of the rep range, then add a small amount of load and repeat.

parsedWorkout.title: Classic Bodybuilding Legs (Quads/Hams/Glutes/Calves) — 75 min
parsedWorkout.description: Hypertrophy-focused lower body session with heavy compounds first, then targeted machine work to fully fatigue quads, hamstrings, glutes, and calves.

exercises.notes: Work up to challenging sets while keeping 1–2 reps in reserve. Brace hard, controlled descent, drive up through mid-foot.
Place feet shoulder-width; control the bottom position and avoid bouncing. Stop 1–2 reps shy of form breakdown.
Squeeze quads at the top for 1 second; keep hips down and avoid swinging the stack.
Hinge at hips with a neutral spine; shins mostly vertical. Lower until hamstrings are loaded, then stand tall without hyperextending.
Pause 1 second at lockout with ribs down and pelvis neutral. Aim for full hip extension driven by glutes.
Control the eccentric for 2–3 seconds; keep hips pinned to the pad and avoid cutting range short.
Use a full stretch at the bottom (1–2 seconds) and a strong peak contraction at the top (1 second). Avoid bouncing.

tips: For classic bodybuilding stimulus, prioritize strict form and controlled eccentrics (2–3 seconds down) on most sets.
Use progressive overload: add 2.5–5% load or 1 rep per set week-to-week while maintaining target rep ranges.
Keep compounds 1–2 reps in reserve; push isolations closer to failure (0–1 RIR) on the final set.
If time runs tight, shorten rest only on isolations—not on squats/RDLs where performance matters most.

parsedWorkout.title: Strength Focus Upper Body (Chest/Back/Shoulders)
parsedWorkout.description: 60-minute strength-focused session emphasizing heavy compound presses/rows with cable and dumbbell accessories for balanced pec, lat, and delt development.

exercises.notes: Barbell bench press. Perform 2–4 ramp-up sets before your first working set. Use a controlled descent, brief pause near the chest, and drive feet into the floor for leg tension.
Barbell bent over row. Brace hard, keep torso angle consistent, and pull to lower ribs/upper waist. Avoid jerking; aim for powerful but controlled reps.
Barbell overhead press. Squeeze glutes and abs to prevent leaning back; bar travels close to the face then finishes over midfoot. Stop 1 rep shy of form breakdown.
Lat pulldown. Use a slight lean back (not a swing), pull elbows down toward your sides, and pause briefly at the bottom to reinforce lat engagement.
Cable crossover. Keep shoulders down and back; think 'hug the tree' to bring biceps toward midline. Maintain a slight elbow bend throughout.
Cable face pull. Pull toward nose/forehead with elbows high; finish with external rotation (knuckles back) to hit rear delts and upper back.
Dumbbell lateral raise. Slight forward lean, raise to just below shoulder height, and control the lowering phase; avoid shrugging.

tips: Progression: when you hit all sets/reps with clean form, add 2.5–5 lb to barbell lifts next session; for cables/dumbbells add the smallest increment or 1–2 reps before adding load.
Keep 1–2 reps in reserve on the main lifts (especially overhead press) to maintain quality and recover well for consistent strength gains.
Rest strictly on compounds (2–3 minutes) to keep performance high; shorter rests are reserved for accessories.
Use ramp-up sets to reach working weight without fatigue (e.g., bar x 10, 50% x 5, 70% x 3, 80–85% x 1, then working sets).

parsedWorkout.title: Lower Body Strength (Quads/Hamstrings/Glutes) — 60 min
parsedWorkout.description: Strength-focused lower-body session emphasizing heavy compound lifts first, then targeted machine work for quads and hamstrings. Aim for crisp technique and progressive overload.

exercises.notes: Work up with 2–4 ramp sets before your first work set. Brace hard, keep bar path over mid-foot, and stop each rep with control (no bouncing).
Hinge back with a neutral spine, slight knee bend, and keep the bar close to the legs. Pause 1 sec near mid-shin if you lose hamstring tension.
Chin tucked, ribs down. Drive through mid-foot/heel and lock out with glutes (avoid over-arching the low back).
Use a controlled descent (2–3 sec) and keep knees tracking over toes. Choose depth you can own without hips lifting off the pad/back support.
Set the pad so knees align with the machine pivot. Fully control the eccentric; avoid hips popping up.
Use a smooth tempo and a brief squeeze at the top. Stop short of any knee pain; adjust seat/back position to keep tension on quads.

tips: Strength loading: keep 1–2 reps in reserve on the heavy work sets; add 2.5–5 lb next week if all sets hit clean reps.
Prioritize long rests (2–3 min) on squats/RDLs/hip thrusts to maintain bar speed and quality reps.
Technique cue for every rep: brace before you descend/hinge, then exhale after the sticking point while maintaining tension.
If time runs short, keep the main lifts intact and reduce accessory sets by 1 (not the other way around).

parsedWorkout.title: 90-Min Strength Focus: Squat, Bench, Deadlift + Row
parsedWorkout.description: Strength-focused session targeting quads (upper legs), pectorals (chest), and spinal erectors/back with barbell and dumbbell compounds plus a controlled accessory press.

exercises.notes: Barbell squat: take 2–4 ramp-up warm-up sets before your working sets. Brace hard, keep bar path over midfoot, and stop 1–2 reps shy of failure.
Barbell deadlift: treat as a top-priority strength lift. Build tension before the pull, push the floor away, and lock out by driving hips through (no hyperextension).
Barbell bench press: shoulders set (retract/depress), consistent touch point, and drive feet into the floor for leg drive. Use a controlled descent.
Incline dumbbell bench press: keep wrists stacked, elbows ~30–45° from torso, and stop short of bouncing at the bottom to keep tension on pecs.

sections.name: Upper Body Pull (Back Thickness + Support for Spine)

exercises.notes: Barbell bent over row: hinge to a stable torso angle, brace like a deadlift, and pull toward lower ribs. Avoid jerking—pause briefly at the top.

tips: Use ramp-up warm-up sets on the first 2 lifts (squat and bench) and at least 2 on deadlift; working sets should feel like ~RPE 7–9 (1–3 reps in reserve).
Prioritize long rest on heavy sets (2–4 min) to keep bar speed and technique consistent; shorten rest only on the accessory movement.
Progression: add 2.5–5 lb each week to squat/bench and 5–10 lb to deadlift as long as you hit all reps with solid form; otherwise repeat the load next session.

parsedWorkout.title: HIT Upper Push/Pull (Chest, Back, Shoulders) — 45 min
parsedWorkout.description: High-intensity upper-body session focused on pectorals, lats, and delts using leverage machine, dumbbells, and cables. Work close to failure with controlled tempo and strict form.

exercises.notes: Use 1–2 ramp-up warm-up sets before Set 1. Work sets at ~0–1 reps in reserve (RIR). Lower 2–3 sec, press hard without bouncing.
Cables slightly below shoulder height; squeeze and hold 1 sec at peak. Keep shoulders down/back to stay on pecs.
Drive elbows down toward hips; pause 1 sec at the bottom. Avoid swinging—keep torso stable.
Pull to lower ribs/upper stomach, squeeze shoulder blades together briefly, then control the return to full stretch.
Keep ribs down and glutes tight; press in a slight arc. Stop 1–2 reps before form breaks, then progress load next week.
Single-arm if possible for better line of pull. Lead with the elbow; stop around shoulder height; keep traps relaxed.
Pull rope toward nose/forehead with elbows high; rotate hands back at the end to hit rear delts. Strict, no body English.

tips: HIT focus: take the final work set of each exercise to near-failure (0–1 RIR) while keeping reps controlled and consistent.
Use 1–2 progressive warm-up (ramp) sets before the first heavy exercise for each muscle group; keep warm-ups easy and don’t fatigue.
Track loads/reps and aim to add 1 rep or a small weight increase when you hit the top of the rep range with clean form.
Keep rest periods honest (60–90s) and avoid extra volume—quality, intensity, and execution drive results in HIT.

parsedWorkout.title: 45-Min Full-Body HIT (Leverage Machine + Dumbbells)
parsedWorkout.description: High-intensity full-body session using controlled reps, short-to-moderate rest, and near-failure effort on working sets to maintain overall fitness and strength.

exercises.notes: Use 1 lighter ramp-up set before Set 1. Work sets: controlled 2–3 sec down, drive up hard; stop 0–1 reps short of form breakdown.
Hinge at hips with a neutral spine; feel stretch in hamstrings. Keep dumbbells close to legs and avoid bouncing at the bottom.
Press with shoulder blades set back; control the lowering. Aim for near-failure on the final set.
Pull elbows toward hips, pause 1 sec at peak contraction. Keep torso stable—no jerking.
Brace core and avoid over-arching low back. If reps slow, keep form strict and end the set.
Exhale as you crunch; keep lower back controlled. Hold the top contraction briefly rather than pulling with the neck.

tips: HIT target: choose a load that brings you within 0–2 reps of technical failure on each working set; increase load when you exceed the rep target with clean form.
Keep reps controlled (especially the lowering phase) and avoid momentum—quality intensity beats speed.
Use 1–2 quick ramp-up sets for the first lower-body and first upper-body movement; don’t count them as working sets to preserve intensity.
Rest just enough to repeat strong sets (typically 60–90s). If performance drops sharply, add 15–30s rather than reducing form quality.

parsedWorkout.title: 30-Min HIT Lower Body Muscle Builder (Barbell + Leverage Machine)
parsedWorkout.description: High-intensity lower-body session focused on quads, hamstrings, glutes, and calves using low-to-moderate volume and near-failure effort.

exercises.notes: Take 2–4 progressive warm-up sets before Set 1. Work sets: controlled 2–3s lowering, drive up hard; stop at 0–1 reps in reserve (RIR).
Hinge at hips, slight knee bend, keep bar close. Feel hamstrings stretch; pause briefly near mid-shin, then stand tall without overextending.
Chin tucked, ribs down, posterior pelvic tilt at the top. Pause 1s at lockout and control the descent.
Full range with a 1s squeeze in the contracted position. Keep hips pinned to the seat and avoid momentum.
2s stretch at the bottom, 1s hard squeeze at the top. Keep reps smooth; stop when you can’t hit full range.

tips: HIT rule: after warm-ups, make your working sets brutally focused—aim for 0–1 RIR with clean technique (no sloppy reps).
Keep transitions tight: pre-load the next station and start your rest timer immediately after each set.
Progression: add 2.5–5 lb (or one machine increment) when you hit the top of the rep range with the same form; otherwise, add reps first.
Control eccentrics (2–3 seconds down) to increase stimulus without adding extra sets.
If recovery stalls, keep intensity high but reduce a set (not effort) before lowering the load.

parsedWorkout.title: 30-Min Full-Body Get-Lean Endurance Circuit (DB/KB/Bodyweight)
parsedWorkout.description: Full-body muscular endurance session using short rests and moderate-to-high reps to drive conditioning and calorie burn while maintaining good form. Move briskly, keep loads moderate, and prioritize consistent pacing.

exercises.notes: Stay light on your feet; keep shoulders relaxed and breathe steadily.
Drive knees up with control; keep ribs down and land softly.
Hinge (not squat). Snap hips through, keep spine neutral, and let the bell float.
Keep elbows close, chest tall, and knees tracking over toes. Use a tempo you can sustain.
12 reps per side. Pull elbow toward hip, pause briefly at the top, avoid torso twisting.
Maintain a straight line head-to-heel; stop 1–2 reps before form breaks.
10 reps per side. Clean smoothly (no banging forearm), brace hard overhead, control the lower.
Hold for 45 seconds. Squeeze glutes, keep ribs down, and push the floor away.

tips: Choose loads that let you finish each set with ~2 reps in reserve (RPE ~8) while keeping rest times strict.
For endurance focus, keep transitions quick and consistent; aim for smooth pacing rather than max effort early.
If you need a progression: add 1–2 reps per set first, then increase weight slightly once you can hit all targets cleanly.
Prioritize form under fatigue: neutral spine on swings/rows, braced core on presses, full-body tension on push-ups/planks.

parsedWorkout.title: Upper Body Muscular Endurance (Lean Focus) — 45 min
parsedWorkout.description: Muscular endurance session targeting chest, back, shoulders, and arms using dumbbells, cables, and bands. Higher reps, shorter rest, and steady tempo to drive fatigue and conditioning.

exercises.notes: Keep ribs down and shoulders away from ears; pull band to chest level and pause 1 second each rep.
Lead with elbows, rotate hands back at the end; avoid shrugging and keep neck relaxed.
Controlled 2–3 sec lower, slight pause, press smoothly. Stop 1–2 reps short of failure on sets 1–2.
Drive elbows back, squeeze shoulder blades together, and avoid leaning too far back.
Brace core and glutes; press slightly back over the head at the top without arching the low back.
Keep elbows pinned to your sides; fully straighten and squeeze at the top without swinging.
Elbows stay tucked; pause 1 second at lockout and control the return.

tips: Use a consistent tempo (about 2–3 seconds down, 1 second up) and keep rest strict (30–45s) to emphasize muscular endurance.
Choose loads that land you in an RPE 7–9 range: challenging but clean form, with 0–2 reps in reserve on most sets.
To progress week-to-week, first add reps within the target range, then add a small amount of load while keeping rest the same.
For a lean-focused session, keep transitions quick and avoid long phone breaks; aim for steady work density across the 45 minutes.

parsedWorkout.title: Dumbbell Upper Body (Classic Bodybuilding) — Chest/Back/Shoulders/Arms
parsedWorkout.description: A 60-minute classic bodybuilding session using only dumbbells, focused on hypertrophy and balanced upper-body development (chest, lats, delts, biceps, triceps).

exercises.notes: Control the lowering (2–3 sec), slight pause near the chest, press smoothly. Keep shoulders packed down/back.
Row toward the hip to bias lats. Keep torso stable and avoid twisting; pause briefly at the top.
Brace your core and glutes; press slightly back over the shoulders. Don’t over-arch the low back.
Soft bend in elbows; stretch under control and squeeze pecs at the top without clanking dumbbells.
Lead with elbows, raise to shoulder height, slight forward torso lean. Avoid shrugging to keep tension on side delts.
Hinge at hips with a flat back; move arms out and back (not straight up). Keep the motion controlled.
Neutral grip; keep elbows close to ribs. Control the eccentric to load the brachialis/forearms.
Keep upper arms mostly vertical; hinge only at elbows. Avoid flaring ribs—brace and keep core tight.

tips: Use bodybuilding tempo: controlled lowering (2–3 seconds) and smooth, strong concentric; stop 1–2 reps shy of failure on compounds and 0–1 RIR on isolations.
Progress weekly by adding 1–2 reps per set until you hit the top of the rep range, then increase dumbbell load slightly and repeat.
Keep rest strict: 90s for big presses/rows/shoulder press, 45–60s for raises/flys/arms to maintain density within 60 minutes.
Prioritize joint-friendly form: shoulders down/back on presses and flys, stable torso on rows, and avoid shrugging during lateral raises.

parsedWorkout.title: 30-Min Classic Bodybuilding Full-Body (DB + Machines)
parsedWorkout.description: A time-efficient full-body session using classic bodybuilding rep ranges (mostly 8–12) with controlled tempo and moderate rests. Prioritizes big movements first, then targeted arm and core work.

exercises.notes: Leg press: 2-sec lower, brief pause near the bottom, drive through mid-foot. Stop 1–2 reps short of failure on sets 1–2.
Dumbbell Romanian deadlift: soft knees, hips back, keep DBs close to legs. Feel hamstrings stretch; don’t chase the floor with a rounded back.
Dumbbell bench press: shoulder blades tucked, wrists stacked over elbows. Lower under control; press up without bouncing.
Machine row: lead with elbows, squeeze lats mid-back for 1 sec, avoid shrugging. Keep torso stable.
Dumbbell shoulder press: brace your core and glutes, press slightly back (not straight forward). Stop short of locking out hard if shoulders feel cranky.
Hammer curl: keep elbows pinned to sides, control the lowering for 2–3 seconds.
Overhead tricep extension: ribs down, elbows point forward/up. Use a full stretch overhead without flaring elbows wide.
Plank: 45 seconds per set. Squeeze glutes, push the floor away, and keep a straight line from head to heels.

tips: Use a classic bodybuilding effort level: aim for ~1–2 reps in reserve on most sets, then push the final set of each main lift closer to near-failure with clean form.
Keep tempo controlled (about 2 seconds down, 1 second up) to maximize tension and make moderate loads effective in a short session.
If time is tight, superset the Accessories section (hammer curl + overhead tricep extension) with minimal transition, then finish with planks.

parsedWorkout.title: Classic Bodybuilding Upper Body (Chest/Back/Delts/Arms) — 45 min
parsedWorkout.description: Hypertrophy-focused upper-body session using dumbbells, cables, and leverage machines. Prioritizes compounds first, then isolation work for a classic bodybuilding pump.

exercises.notes: Control the negative (2–3 sec). Keep shoulder blades retracted and elbows ~45° from torso.
Slight bend in elbows; bring hands together without letting shoulders roll forward. Pause 1 sec at peak.
Lead with elbows; avoid leaning back. Squeeze shoulder blades together at the finish.
Brace your core; press slightly back over mid-foot. Stop 1–2 reps shy of form breakdown.
Pull to eyebrow level with elbows high and wide. Focus on rear delts/upper back, not biceps.
Keep upper arms pinned back; full stretch at the bottom and controlled curl up.
Elbows stay tucked and fixed; extend fully and squeeze triceps hard for 1 sec each rep.

tips: Use a bodybuilding effort level: finish most sets with ~1–2 reps in reserve; push the last isolation set closer to near-failure with clean form.
Keep rest periods honest: longer for heavy presses/rows (90–120s), shorter for isolation (45–75s) to drive metabolic stress.
Progression goal: add 1 rep per set week-to-week until you hit the top of the rep range, then increase load slightly and repeat.
Prioritize technique: controlled eccentrics, full ROM, and consistent setup (bench angle, seat height, cable path) for repeatable overload.

parsedWorkout.title: Classic Bodybuilding Push Day (Chest/Shoulders/Triceps)
parsedWorkout.description: Hypertrophy-focused push workout using heavy compounds first, then targeted isolation for chest, delts, and triceps. Aim for controlled eccentrics and strong contractions.

exercises.notes: Barbell bench press: 2–3 warm-up sets before working sets. Use a controlled 2–3 sec lower, light pause on chest, drive up with leg tension.
Incline dumbbell bench press: set bench to a moderate incline (not too steep). Keep shoulder blades pinned and stop 1 rep shy of failure on the first set.
Cable crossover: slight forward lean, soft elbows, bring hands together and squeeze chest for 1 second each rep. Prioritize tension over load.
Barbell overhead press: glutes and abs tight, bar path close to face, finish with biceps near ears. Avoid excessive back lean.
Cable lateral raise: keep the cable slightly in front of the body, lead with elbows, and stop around shoulder height. Slow negative to keep delts loaded.
Close grip bench press: hands just inside shoulder width, elbows ~30–45° from torso. Touch lower chest and press straight up to emphasize triceps.
Tricep pushdown: keep upper arms fixed, full lockout with a hard squeeze, controlled return. Use a weight that keeps form strict.

tips: Use classic bodybuilding execution: controlled eccentrics (2–3 seconds), full range of motion, and a strong peak contraction on isolation work.
Progression target: add 1 rep per set week-to-week until you hit the top of the rep goal, then add a small amount of weight and repeat.
Keep 1–2 reps in reserve on heavy compounds most sets; push closer to technical failure on the final set of isolation movements.

parsedWorkout.title: Get Lean: Classic Back + Biceps (75 min)
parsedWorkout.description: Classic bodybuilding session emphasizing lat width, upper-back thickness, and biceps hypertrophy with moderate rest to support leanness and conditioning.

exercises.notes: Light-to-moderate load. Lead with elbows, pause 1 sec at full contraction, keep ribs down to avoid lower-back arching.
Use full ROM: dead-hang to chest-to-bar intent. If needed, use controlled negatives to hit target reps.
Hinge to a stable torso angle, pull bar to lower ribs, 2–3 sec controlled eccentric. Avoid jerking or standing up each rep.
Drive elbows down and slightly back, stop short of shrugging. 1-sec squeeze at the bottom to emphasize lats.
Neutral spine, initiate by pulling shoulders back then elbows. Keep chest tall and avoid rocking.
Keep elbows slightly in front of torso, no hip drive. Control the lowering for 2–3 seconds.
Let arms hang back to stretch the long head; keep shoulders pinned. Stop 1–2 reps short of form breakdown.
Wrists neutral, elbows close. Focus on brachialis/forearm contribution for arm thickness.

tips: Work mostly at RPE 7–9 (about 1–3 reps in reserve) and add load or reps week-to-week while keeping form strict.
For a lean-focused bodybuilding feel, keep rest tight (60–90s), but don’t rush heavy compounds—quality reps first.
Use controlled eccentrics (2–3 seconds down) and brief pauses at peak contraction on rows/curls to maximize stimulus with moderate loads.
